{"title_page": "Jonathan Shaw (photographer)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata\n| fetchwikidata=ALL\n| dateformat = dmy\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Shaw''' is a British photographer and educator. He uses the camera as an instrument of both scientific record and aesthetic exploration.\n\n== Photography ==\n\nShaw's commissioned work includes pieces for [[Volkswagen|Volkswagen UK]], the Manhattan Loft Corporation, and Nigel Coates' book ''Guide to Ecstacity'' published by Laurence King Publishing.<ref group=\"n\">[http://www.nigelcoates.com/project/ecstacity_book \"Guide to Ecstacity\"] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120402153636/http://www.nigelcoates.com/project/ecstacity_book |date= 2 April 2012 }}</ref> His work has been shown at [[Leeds Beckett University|Leeds Met]] Gallery, [[Goethe Institute]] in Dresden, Germany, [[Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery]], 'Penny School Gallery' as part of the Muybridge Centenary celebrations in Kingston upon Thames, Lanchester Gallery (Coventry), F-Stop Media (Bath) and at the Howard Gardens Gallery as part of the International Festival of Contemporary Time Based Arts, Cardiff.\n\nIn 2003 ''Time|Motion'', published by Dewi Lewis,<ref group=\"n\" name=\"dltimemotion\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.dewilewispublishing.com/PHOTOGRAPHY/TIMEMOTION.html# |title= Time{{!}}Motion published by Dewi Lewis |access-date=19 September 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120212110142/http://www.dewilewispublishing.com/PHOTOGRAPHY/TIMEMOTION.html# |archive-date= 12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> placed Shaw's work alongside that by [[Eadweard Muybridge]] and [[Harold Eugene Edgerton]]. In 2004 he was nominated for the [[Paul Hamlyn Award]].\n\nIn 2011 his work appeared in [[Maarten Vanvolsem]]'s book ''The Art of Strip Photography: Making Still Images with a Moving Camera.''<ref group=\"n\">[http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100871850 \"The Art of Strip Photography: Making Still Images with a Moving Camera\"], [[Cornell University Press]].</ref>\n\n== Academia ==\n\nShaw was formerly Associate Head of the Media Department within [[Coventry University]]'s School of Art and Design, where he has worked with [[Jonathan Worth (photographer)|Jonathan Worth]] and Matt Johnston to pioneer free and open undergraduate photography classes #picbod<ref group=\"n\">Picbod's website was http://www.picbod.org {{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> and #phonar.<ref>Phonar's website is [http://www.phonar.org here].</ref> These classes have been accessed by thousands of students all around the globe<ref>[https://www.wired.com/rawfile/2011/08/free-online-class-shakes-up-photo-education/ \"RAW file: Free Online Class Shakes Up Photo Education\"]</ref> with podcasts on the Photographic Mediations channel on iTunesU being accessed over 700,000 times.<ref>[http://photography.covmedia.co.uk/2011/08/22/itunes-u-features-photographic-mediations-podcasts-as-hits-pass-700000/ \"Photography Class opens its doors to the world\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426201721/http://photography.covmedia.co.uk/2011/08/22/itunes-u-features-photographic-mediations-podcasts-as-hits-pass-700000/ |date=26 April 2012 }}, covmedia.co.uk.</ref>\n\nHe was chair of the Association for Photography in Higher Education from 2014-2017.<ref name=\"APHE\">{{cite web |publisher=Association for Photography in Higher Education |title=About |url=http://aphe.ac.uk/about/ |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> He sits on the editorial board of ''[[Media Practice & Education]]'',<ref name=\"MPE\">{{cite web |title=Media Practice and Education Editorial Board |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/action/journalInformation?show=editorialBoard&journalCode=rjmp21 |publisher=Taylor and Francis |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> and was a guest editor of a \"special disrupted issue\" of the ''[[Journal of Media Practice]]'' in May 2018.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shaw |first1=Jonathan |last2=Morini |first2=Luca |last3=Adema |first3=Janneke |title=Disrupting the Journal of Media Practice |journal=Media Practice and Education |date=22 May 2018 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20137 |doi=10.1080/14682753.2017.1362167}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, he is director of Coventry University's 'Disruptive Media Learning Lab'.<ref>{{cite web |title=About DMLL |url=https://dmll.org.uk/about/ |publisher=Coventry University |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n===Publications by Shaw===\n*''Crash.'' [[The New Art Gallery Walsall]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cornerhouse.org/bookstore/product/jonathan-shaw |title=Crash published by New Art Gallery Walsall |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212112712/http://www.cornerhouse.org/bookstore/product/jonathan-shaw |archive-date=12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |publisher=Cornerhouse}}</ref>\n*''Newfotoscapes.'' A multi-platform open book (2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newfotoscapes.org/ |title=Newfotoscapes multi-platform open book |publisher=[[Library of Birmingham]] }}</ref>\n\n''Newfotoscapes'' was selected as one of Lens Culture's \"Best Photobooks of 2014\".<ref name=\"LensCulture\">{{cite web |title=2014 Photobooks of the Year - Photobooks selected by the editors LensCulture |url=https://www.lensculture.com/articles/lensculture-editors-2014-photobooks-of-the-year |publisher=LensCulture |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Publications with contributions by Shaw===\n*''Time|Motion.'' [[Dewi Lewis]] (2003)<ref group=\"n\" name=\"dltimemotion\" />\n*''re(collect.'' Pavilion (2006)\n\n==Exhibitions==\n*Leeds Met Gallery commissioned a piece of work by Shaw titled 'If only they had eyes' (2011)<ref>[https://archive.is/20120803220243/http://www.leedsguide.co.uk/review/feature/junction-project/19094 \"Leeds Guide: The Junction Project\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm \"Leeds Metropolitan University: Junction Project\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707023006/http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm |date= 7 July 2011 }}</ref> as part of 'Junction', a citywide art project.<ref>[http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm \"Leeds Metropolitan University: Junction Project\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707023006/http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm |date= 7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n*'On The Move' at Estorick Collection (2010).<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.estorickcollection.com/exhibitions/On_the_Move.php# |title=On the Move at Estorick Collection 2010 |access-date= 14 November 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120319234147/http://www.estorickcollection.com/exhibitions/On_the_Move.php# |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/reviews/on-the-move-estorick-collection-london-1870027.html \"Independent Review: On the Move at Estorick Collection 2010\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB126348898108128887 \"On the Move with Director Jonathan Miller, WSJ review\"]</ref>\n*'Crash' at New Art Gallery Walsall UK (2009),<ref>[http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/jonathan-shawcrash \"'Crash' at New Art Gallery Walsall\"]</ref> Leeds Met Gallery UK, Geothe Institute Germany, Lanchester Gallery UK{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*Installation at Frenchgate Centre at Fire, Ice & Light Festival Doncaster, UK (2009)<ref>[http://www.car.chula.ac.th/art/en/?page_id=790 \"Installation at Frenchgate Centre at Fire, Ice & Light Festival Doncaster\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402153636/http://www.car.chula.ac.th/art/en/?page_id=790 |date= 2 April 2012 }}</ref>\n*'(re)collect' at Leeds Met Gallery UK (2006){{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*'Time|Motion' at Birmingham Museums & Art Gallery UK (2003)<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20120320223834/http://www.rhubarb-rhubarb.net/05_exhibitions_archive_details.asp?year=2003&eid=14 \"'Time|Motion' at Birmingham Museums & Art Gallery\"]</ref>\n\n==Collections==\nShaw's work is held in the following public collections:\n*[[Arts Council of England]]{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*[[Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery]]{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*[[Birmingham Central Library]] Photographic Archive{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n\n==Honours and accolades==\n\nShaw is a Fellow of the Royal Photographic Society{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, his blog can't be a source for this. --><ref>[http://jonathan-shaw.com/blog/2010/07/jonathan-receives-fellowship-from-royal-photographic-society/ \"jonathan Shaw made Fellow of the RPS\"]</ref> and is a member of the society's 'Multimedia and Narrative Distinction Panel' alongside Andy Golding (University of Westminster) and [[Daniel Meadows]] among others.<ref>[http://www.rps.org/resources/group_downloads/422-423_Distinction.pdf \"Multimedia and Narrative RPS Distinction announcement PDF\"]{{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> In 2010 the RSA ([[Royal Society of Arts|Royal Society for the encouragement of Arts, Manufactures and Commerce]]) awarded Shaw a fellowship for recognition for his innovation and influential role in developing business and education models in photography.{{Citation needed|date=February 2013}}<!-- No, his blog can't be a source for this. --><ref>[http://jonathan-shaw.com/blog/2010/02/jonathan-becomes-a-fellow-of-the-rsa/ \"Fellowship of the RSA \u2013 Jonathan Shaw\"]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n<references group=\"n\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://pureportal.coventry.ac.uk/en/persons/jonathan-shaw Staff Profile] at Coventry University\n*[http://jonathan-shaw.com/ Jonathan Shaw Photographic Website]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shaw, Jonathan}}\n[[Category:British photographers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Academics of Coventry University]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=September 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person/Wikidata\n| fetchwikidata=ALL\n| dateformat = dmy\n}}\n\n'''Jonathan Shaw''' is a British photographer and educator. He uses the camera as an instrument of both scientific record and aesthetic exploration.\n\n== Photography ==\n\nShaw's commissioned work includes pieces for [[Volkswagen|Volkswagen UK]], the Manhattan Loft Corporation, and Nigel Coates' book ''Guide to Ecstacity'' published by Laurence King Publishing.<ref group=\"n\">[http://www.nigelcoates.com/project/ecstacity_book \"Guide to Ecstacity\"] {{webarchive |url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120402153636/http://www.nigelcoates.com/project/ecstacity_book |date= 2 April 2012 }}</ref> His work has been shown at [[Leeds Beckett University|Leeds Met]] Gallery, [[Goethe Institute]] in Dresden, Germany, [[Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery]], 'Penny School Gallery' as part of the Muybridge Centenary celebrations in Kingston upon Thames, Lanchester Gallery (Coventry), F-Stop Media (Bath) and at the Howard Gardens Gallery as part of the International Festival of Contemporary Time Based Arts, Cardiff.\n\nIn 2003 ''Time|Motion'', published by Dewi Lewis,<ref group=\"n\" name=\"dltimemotion\">{{Cite web |url= http://www.dewilewispublishing.com/PHOTOGRAPHY/TIMEMOTION.html# |title= Time{{!}}Motion published by Dewi Lewis |access-date=19 September 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120212110142/http://www.dewilewispublishing.com/PHOTOGRAPHY/TIMEMOTION.html# |archive-date= 12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> placed Shaw's work alongside that by [[Eadweard Muybridge]] and [[Harold Eugene Edgerton]]. In 2004 he was nominated for the [[Paul Hamlyn Award]].\n\nIn 2011 his work appeared in [[Maarten Vanvolsem]]'s book ''The Art of Strip Photography: Making Still Images with a Moving Camera.''<ref group=\"n\">[http://www.cornellpress.cornell.edu/book/?GCOI=80140100871850 \"The Art of Strip Photography: Making Still Images with a Moving Camera\"], [[Cornell University Press]].</ref>\n\n== Academia ==\n\nShaw was formerly Associate Head of the Media Department within [[Coventry University]]'s School of Art and Design, where he has worked with [[Jonathan Worth (photographer)|Jonathan Worth]] and Matt Johnston to pioneer free and open undergraduate photography classes #picbod<ref group=\"n\">Picbod's website was http://www.picbod.org {{dead link|date=April 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}.</ref> and #phonar.<ref>Phonar's website is [http://www.phonar.org here].</ref> These classes have been accessed by thousands of students all around the globe<ref>[https://www.wired.com/rawfile/2011/08/free-online-class-shakes-up-photo-education/ \"RAW file: Free Online Class Shakes Up Photo Education\"]</ref> with podcasts on the Photographic Mediations channel on iTunesU being accessed over 700,000 times.<ref>[http://photography.covmedia.co.uk/2011/08/22/itunes-u-features-photographic-mediations-podcasts-as-hits-pass-700000/ \"Photography Class opens its doors to the world\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426201721/http://photography.covmedia.co.uk/2011/08/22/itunes-u-features-photographic-mediations-podcasts-as-hits-pass-700000/ |date=26 April 2012 }}, covmedia.co.uk.</ref>\n\nHe was chair of the Association for Photography in Higher Education from 2014-2017.<ref name=\"APHE\">{{cite web |publisher=Association for Photography in Higher Education |title=About |url=http://aphe.ac.uk/about/ |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> He sits on the editorial board of ''[[Media Practice & Education]]'',<ref name=\"MPE\">{{cite web |title=Media Practice and Education Editorial Board |url=https://www.tandfonline.com/action/journalInformation?show=editorialBoard&journalCode=rjmp21 |publisher=Taylor and Francis |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref> and was a guest editor of a \"special disrupted issue\" of the ''[[Journal of Media Practice]]'' in May 2018.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Shaw |first1=Jonathan |last2=Morini |first2=Luca |last3=Adema |first3=Janneke |title=Disrupting the Journal of Media Practice |journal=Media Practice and Education |date=22 May 2018 |volume=19 |issue=1 |pages=1\u20137 |doi=10.1080/14682753.2017.1362167}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2020, he is director of the University's 'Disruptive Media Learning Lab'.<ref>{{cite web |title=About DMLL |url=https://dmll.org.uk/about/ |publisher=Coventry University |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\n===Publications by Shaw===\n*''Crash.'' [[The New Art Gallery Walsall]] (2009)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cornerhouse.org/bookstore/product/jonathan-shaw |title=Crash published by New Art Gallery Walsall |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120212112712/http://www.cornerhouse.org/bookstore/product/jonathan-shaw |archive-date=12 February 2012 |url-status=dead |publisher=Cornerhouse}}</ref>\n*''Newfotoscapes.'' A multi-platform open book (2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://newfotoscapes.org/ |title=Newfotoscapes multi-platform open book |publisher=[[Library of Birmingham]] }}</ref>\n\n''Newfotoscapes'' was selected as one of Lens Culture's \"Best Photobooks of 2014\".<ref name=\"LensCulture\">{{cite web |title=2014 Photobooks of the Year - Photobooks selected by the editors LensCulture |url=https://www.lensculture.com/articles/lensculture-editors-2014-photobooks-of-the-year |publisher=LensCulture |accessdate=28 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Publications with contributions by Shaw===\n*''Time|Motion.'' [[Dewi Lewis]] (2003)<ref group=\"n\" name=\"dltimemotion\" />\n*''re(collect.'' Pavilion (2006)\n\n==Exhibitions==\n*Leeds Met Gallery commissioned a piece of work by Shaw titled 'If only they had eyes' (2011)<ref>[https://archive.is/20120803220243/http://www.leedsguide.co.uk/review/feature/junction-project/19094 \"Leeds Guide: The Junction Project\"]</ref><ref>[http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm \"Leeds Metropolitan University: Junction Project\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707023006/http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm |date= 7 July 2011 }}</ref> as part of 'Junction', a citywide art project.<ref>[http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm \"Leeds Metropolitan University: Junction Project\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110707023006/http://www.leedsmet.ac.uk/arts/E43822F76A7D4D1194B4FA7D303C1594.htm |date= 7 July 2011 }}</ref>\n*'On The Move' at Estorick Collection (2010).<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.estorickcollection.com/exhibitions/On_the_Move.php# |title=On the Move at Estorick Collection 2010 |access-date= 14 November 2011 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120319234147/http://www.estorickcollection.com/exhibitions/On_the_Move.php# |archive-date=19 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/art/reviews/on-the-move-estorick-collection-london-1870027.html \"Independent Review: On the Move at Estorick Collection 2010\"]</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB126348898108128887 \"On the Move with Director Jonathan Miller, WSJ review\"]</ref>\n*'Crash' at New Art Gallery Walsall UK (2009),<ref>[http://www.thenewartgallerywalsall.org.uk/whats-on/exhibition/jonathan-shawcrash \"'Crash' at New Art Gallery Walsall\"]</ref> Leeds Met Gallery UK, Geothe Institute Germany, Lanchester Gallery UK{{cn|date=September 2019}}\n*Installation at Frenchgate Centre at Fire, Ice & Light Festival Doncaster, UK (2009)<ref>[http://www.car.chula.ac.th/art/en/?page_id=790 \"Installation at Frenchgate Centre at Fire, Ice & Light Festival Doncaster\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120402153636/